Analysis of the Growth of Top Streamers on Twitch¶

Image from kaggle

Grace Kim¶

Introduction¶

The industry of gaming is very large now with millions of dollars being invested into Esports and other new companies. While the onset of the pandemic has not been kind to many companies, Twitch's viewership and engagement metrics skyrocketed last year, thanks to quarantined consumers looking for entertainment. Twitch allows gamers to live-broadcast their videogames and is easily the undisputed champion of its arena. It has reached new heights during the pandemic, becoming a go-to entertainment destination for consumers confined to their homes around the world. There are now 7 million streamers who broadcast themselves playing video games each month—nearly twice as many as there were before the pandemic began. While many professional sports were off the air in the first half of 2020, Twitch was still there, stronger than ever.

The purpose of this project is to gain more insight on the growth of the top Twitch streamers to see whether there are patterns in the success of a streamer. This could prove beneficial for new streamers who want to improve their popularity by mimicking patterns of the top streamers. Seasoned streamers could also benefit from this project by gaining insight on things like the number of viewers, number of active viewers, followers gained and many other relevant columns. We ultimately want to learn how these Twitch streamers became so popular through their statistics and be able to predict any trends in growth for other potential streamers.

You can learn more about Twitch here: https://www.twitch.tv/

From the Twitch dataset, we got 11 columns which consists of:

  • Channel Name
  • Watch time (in minutes)
  • Stream time (in minutes)
  • Peak viewers
  • Average viewers
  • Followers
  • Followers gained
  • Views gained
  • Partnered
  • Mature (+18)
  • Language

The columns are, for the most part, self-explanatory. To elaborate on a few columns, the Peak viewers consists of the maximum number of viewers a particular streamer has, the Partnered column is whether that streamer is partnered with Twitch in a program for those who are committed to streaming and are ready to level up from Affiliate.

Tidying and Modifying the Data¶

While the data we obtained was already ready for use, we do want to modify some of the data to make the exploratory data analysis a bit simpler in the future. I removed the Watch time(Minutes), Stream time(Minutes), Peak viewers, and Language columns since I will not be needing those values since they provide no useful information for the purposes of this tutorial. This condenses the data in our dataframe to only the relevant information.

The rest of the information within the dataframe is information that we care about. I did not find the need to create any additional dataframes or columns within our dataset since I did not find it necessary for purposes of this tutorial and the exploratory data analysis.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

We want to see what kind of correlations we could make from the data to try to figure out if there is a pattern to successful Twitch streamers that improves their overall popularity. We want to compare the different features of each streamer and the overall patterns of their information, so I plotted general plots for the streamers and by top 100 streamers to showcase the impact of a smaller dataset.

Let's begin by visualizing some characteristics of top Twitch streamers.

In [407]:
# mature content's impact on overall popularity
notMature = 0
isMature = 0

for i, row in streamers.iterrows():
    if row['Mature'] == True:
        isMature += 1
    elif row['Mature'] == False:
        notMature += 1

labels = ['True','False']
sizes = [int(isMature),int(notMature)]

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.pie(sizes, labels=labels, autopct='%1.1f%%')
# Equal aspect ratio ensures the pie chart is circular.
ax.axis('equal')  
ax.set_title('+18 Stream or Not', fontsize='15')

plt.show()

print("Number of Streamers who have mature content: " + str(isMature))
print("Number of Streamers who do not have mature content: " + str(notMature))

Number of Streamers who have mature content: 230
Number of Streamers who do not have mature content: 770

Of the top 1000 Twitch streamers in the given dataset, only 230 stream mature, +18, content. Initially, I thought that there would be more streamers that do +18 streams due to the commonly violent nature of many popular videogames. However, upon further analysis, we found that a majority of the top Twitch streamers actually stream content for all ages. This shows that by having certain content for a stream, there is a larger audience available to increase the viewers. Since this is indicative of the top 1000 Twitch streamers, we only get a very general analysis that overall, not having an age requirement may lead to more popularity.

In order to see a more specific impact of mature content, I plot a dataset of just the top 100 Twitch streamers to show that the same statistics among the most successful Twitch streamers.

In [412]:
# Creating a scatterplot of average viewers vs num of followers to see active viewers for top 1000 streamers
diff = []
label = []

# Calculating difference 
for i, row in streamers.iterrows():
    difference = int(row['Followers']) - int(row['Average viewers'])
    diff.append(difference)
    label.append(i+1)
    
# Pushing values into a dataframe
dfdiff = pd.DataFrame({'label': label, 'difference': diff})

# Scatterplot
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
x = dfdiff.label
y = dfdiff.difference

# Random color for display purposes
color = np.random.rand(3,)

for x, y in zip(x, y):
    rgb = np.random.rand(3,)
    plt.scatter(x, y, 8, c=[rgb])

plt.title("Active Followers based on Average Viewers and Popularity", fontsize='15')
plt.xlabel('Channel Rank', fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Number of People(in millions)', fontweight='bold')
Out[412]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Number of People(in millions)')

Using the scatterplot of all 1000 top Twitch streamers, we can now see some pattern among the difference of Average viewers and Followers for each respective Twitch streamer. At first glance, it seems that the data has a bit of a right skew as the difference between the number of Followers and the Average viewers decreases as the ranking of channels lowers. The most popular channels seem to have a large difference between the number of followers and viewers which shows that not all of their followers are always viewing each stream. Despite this, these channels are gaining views somehow, perhaps from an outside factor.

We did come to this conclusion assuming that the average number of viewers is made up of those that also follow the channel. One major factor to consider is that it is possible that not all of the viewers may be followers, so there may be some discrepancies with this as it was not specified in the dataset. In order to continue analyzing this data, we can utilize these plots to draw more conclusions with the help of linear regressions.

Hypothesis Testing and Predicting with Machine Learning¶

In [413]:
# Scatterplot of average viewers vs num of followers
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
x = dfdiff.label
y = dfdiff.difference

    plt.scatter(x, y,8, c=[rgb])

plt.title("Linear Regression for Active Followers and Popularity", fontsize='15')
plt.xlabel('Channel Rank', fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Number of People(in millions)', fontweight='bold')

# NumPy's polyfit to ease interpretation
b, m = polyfit(label, diff, 1)
plt.plot(label, np.multiply(m, label) + b, '-', c='red', lw=2)


x = dfdiff['label'].values.reshape(-1,1)
y = dfdiff['difference'].values.reshape(-1,1)
reg = LinearRegression().fit(x, y)
coef = reg.coef_
intercept = reg.intercept_
print(coef, intercept)

[[-1192.0956248]] [1161916.88821021]

The red line helps with the interpretation and represents the regression line of the difference between the number of Followers and Average viewers for each streamer from most popular to least. Based off of the regression line, the top streamers experience a large difference between the average number of viewers and the number of followers while those less popular tend have less of a difference. This difference from the top most streamers to less popular streamers shows that with popularity comes with a gap between viewers and viewers who follow the channel. The regression shows that more popular channels are more likely to have a larger gap between followers and viewers on average. This means that as a channel becomes more popular, less followers will regularly watch all the content.

The slope supports this hypothesis as it decreases as we move to lower ranked channels. One thing to consider here is that this slope is not indicative of all the information presented to us. So, in order to continue with our hypothesis testing, we need to find the linear regression with information in other columns to find an interation term between popularity and other factors.

More information on linear regression can be found here: https://scipy-lectures.org/packages/scikit-learn/auto_examples/plot_linear_regression.html

The next step is now to make predictions regarding our dataset, specifically with the growth pattern of the top Twitch streamers. We have a general idea of what factors play into a successful streamer and now we are going to make predictions based off of our linear regressions above.

In [416]:
Ranks = list(range(1000))

# Popularity factors
# Create dataframe to hold what factors impact popularity based on earlier linear regressions
factors = pd.DataFrame({'Channel':streamers['Channel'], 'Rank':Ranks, 'Mature':streamers['Mature'], 'Partnered':streamers['Partnered'],\
                       'Active Followers':dfdiff['difference'],'Growth Rate': dfratio['ratio']})

X = factors[['Active Followers','Growth Rate']]
Y = factors['Rank']

x_train, x_test,y_train,y_test = train_test_split(X,Y,test_size =0.2)

clf = LinearRegression()

# Fit the data
clf.fit(x_train,y_train)

# Predict using x_test
pred = clf.predict(x_test)

# Plot how the predicted popularity compares to our current data
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,10))
plt.title('Channel Popularity for Actual and Predicted', fontsize ='15')
plt.xlabel("Rank", weight='bold')
plt.ylabel("Factors", weight='bold')  
sns.distplot(y_test, hist=False, label="Actual", ax=ax)
sns.distplot(pred, hist=False, label="Linear Regression Predictions", ax=ax)
plt.legend(ncol=7)

plt.show()

We have seen how we can split up the dataset into training and testing parts to pass it to the fit function. Also, we have used the linear-regression algorithm to predict the rank of a channel on the basis of its Active Followers and Growth Rate as we found earlier. The predicted and the actual comparison differs at a pretty large scale. While the overall trends are similar, the extent to which the factors impact the Linear Regression Predictions is very extreme and this is understandable due to other human factors that impact the actual data that we could not take into consideration. Examples of these could include the actual content of a stream or the streamer themselves. Despite this, we were able to follow the trend of the actual data in our prediction.

More on Linear Regressions and Split Datasets Using Sklearn can be found here: https://medium.com/the-code-monster/split-a-dataset-into-train-and-test-datasets-using-sk-learn-acc7fd1802e0

Conclusion¶

A key function of using data science with this top Twitch streamer dataset is using behavioral data to build data and see how people discover and move between streams and channels. By looking at the data from the top Twitch streamers, we gain more insight on how their audience reacted to streamers of varying popularity.

With the use of the plots and linear regression lines, we now know which factors have an impact on popularity and ranking of a Twitch channel. Among the top 1000 Twitch streamers, common factors included:

  • Content for all ages (Mature)
  • Twitch Partners
  • An significant amount of active followers
  • A constant growth rate of new viewers and followers

Based on these trends we can say that it is easy to start growth quickly but it gets competitive as the channel gets more popular. This is reasonable since a smaller channel is able to be more personal to each follower but as they grow, it is harder to maintain a personal connection to each account. Growing popular also means more content which not every follower will view which impacted our findings in the Active Follower plot with regression.

As I approached the EDA, I wanted to easily visualize any patterns in the dataset among the top Twitch streamers. The clearest method was using a pie chart to find very common patterns among the channels especially when it came to mature content and whether a channel is a partner. As we progressed through the Exploratory Data Analysis, bar charts and scatter plots made more sense for the large amount of data at hand. In analyzing the EDA portion of our project several conclusions can be made based on the factors that correlate to the reason why certain streamers are more popular than others.

The popularity of a Twitch streamer is very dependent on these factors but also other factors like content and overall likeability which are both difficult to quantify. For that reason, our predictions were not entirely accurate to the original dataset. Our efforts were not a waste, however, because we still were able to mimic a similar trend to the dataset given the factors that we considered for popularity.

Putting in the effort during the EDA allows us to answer important questions on the success of certain streamers and helps other streamers improve their following and views. Like any data analysis, we were able to answer a few questions but also derive more for further analysis. Moving forward, developing a new model on specific streamers given the chronology of their growth in popularity would shed more light on habits that top Twitch streamers do to be successful. While gathering this data, we would need to consider the up and coming streamers and predict those channels growing in popularity. The possibilities are endless when it comes to this and any dataset.

Overall, the trends of the top Twitch streamers can reflect other factors in the world. The increase of viewers shows that people are spending more time indoors or at least in front of an electronic device. The world is constantly changing and with that comes a constant flow of data.
